HW2 Problem 6

(a)

\[\begin{align*} E[X] &= \int_0^1x\frac{1}{B(\alpha,\beta)}x^{\alpha-1}(1-x)^{\beta-1}dx\\ &= \frac{1}{B(\alpha,\beta)}\int_0^1 x^{\alpha}(1-x)^{\beta-1}dx\\ &= \frac{1}{B(\alpha,\beta)}B(\alpha+1,\beta) \;\;\;\; \text{(definition of beta function)} \\ &= \frac{\Gamma(\alpha+\beta)}{\Gamma(\alpha)\Gamma(\beta)}\frac{\Gamma(\alpha+1)\Gamma(\beta)}{\Gamma(\alpha+\beta+1)}\\ &= \frac{\Gamma(\alpha+1)}{\Gamma(\alpha)}\frac{\Gamma(\alpha+\beta)}{\Gamma(\alpha+\beta+1)}\\ &=\frac{\alpha}{\alpha+\beta} \;\;\;\; \text{(Property of gamma function }\Gamma(c+1)=c\Gamma(c)\text{)} \end{align*}\]

HW2 Problem 7

(a)

\[\begin{align*} E[X] &= \sum\limits_{x=0}^{\infty} x\frac{e^{-\lambda}\lambda^x}{x!} = \sum\limits_{x=1}^{\infty} x\frac{e^{-\lambda}\lambda^x}{x!} \;\;\;\; \text{(the first term is 0)} \\ & = \lambda\sum\limits_{x=1}^{\infty} \frac{e^{-\lambda}\lambda^{x-1}}{(x-1)!} = \lambda\sum\limits_{y=0}^{\infty} \frac{e^{-\lambda}\lambda^{y}}{y!} \;\;\;\; \text{(change of variable }y=x-1\text{)} \\ &= \lambda \;\;\;\; \text{(sum of poisson PMFs is equal to 1)} \end{align*}\]

(b)

\[\begin{align*} E[X^2] &= E[X(X-1)] + E[X] \\ &= \sum\limits_{x=0}^{\infty} x(x-1)\frac{e^{-\lambda}\lambda^x}{x!} + E[X] \\ &= \sum\limits_{x=2}^{\infty} x(x-1)\frac{e^{-\lambda}\lambda^x}{x!} + E[X] \;\;\;\; \text{(the first and second terms are 0)} \\ &= \lambda^2\sum\limits_{x=2}^{\infty} \frac{e^{-\lambda}\lambda^{x-2}}{(x-2)!} + E[X] \\ &= \lambda^2\sum\limits_{y=0}^{\infty} \frac{e^{-\lambda}\lambda^{y}}{y!} + E[X] \;\;\;\; \text{(change of variable }y=x-2\text{)} \\ &= \lambda^2+\lambda \\ var(X) &= E[X^2]-E[X]^2 = \lambda. \end{align*}\]

HW2 Problem 9

Solution 1

(a)

Let \(x\) be the number of songs played until you hear a repeated song. That is, \(x-1\) distinct songs have been played and the \(x\)th song is a repeat of one of the previous \(x-1\) songs. Note that,

  • We must play at least \(1\) song before we can hear a repeated song, so \(x \geq 2\).
  • Since there are only \(1000\) unique songs, by song \(1001\), at least one song must be repeated.

Thus, \(X\) can take on values from \(2\) to \(1001\).

To determine the probabilities, suppose the \(x\)th song played is the first repeated song. Then, \[P(X = x) = \frac{\text{$\#$ ways $x$ songs are played with the $x$th song being the only repeated song}}{\text{$\#$ ways to play $x$ songs}}\] Let us first consider the denominator.

  • For the first song played, we have \(1000\) options.
  • Similarly, for the second song, we have \(1000\) options since we have no restrictions on repetition.
  • Continuing, for th \(x\)th song played, we still have \(1000\) options.

Thus, the total number of ways to play \(x\) songs is \(1000^x\).

Now consider the numerator.

  • For the first song played, we have \(1000\) options.
  • However, for the second song, we only have \(999\) options since the first song cannot be played again, otherwise we would have a repetition.
  • Continuing for the \((x-1)\)th song, we have \(1000 - (x-2)\) options since \(x-2\) songs have already been played.
  • For the \(x\)th song there are \(x-1\) options since it must repeat one of the previous \(x-1\) songs.

Thus, the total number of ways to play \((x-1)\) songs with no repeats and \(x\)-th being a repeat of one of the previous \(x-1\) songs is: \[[1000 \cdot (1000 - 1) \cdots (1000 - (x-2))] (x-1) = \frac{1000!}{(1000 - (x-1))!}\cdot(x-1)\]

Combining, we have \[P(X = x) = \frac{1000!(x-1)}{(1000 - (x-1))!\cdot 1000^x} \quad \quad \text{ for } x = 2, 3, ..., 1001 \]

Solution 2 (optional)

Note that the closed form solution for \(P(X = x)\) is not very tractable due to the large factorials. For the sake of calculating the expectation and variance, it is more practical to define \(P(X = x)\) recursively.

Consider \(X=1\). \(P(X=1) = 0\) trivially. \[\begin{eqnarray} P(X=2 \cap X > 1) & = & P(X=2 \cap X > 1| X > 1)P(X > 1) \phantom{00}\text{Definition of conditional probability} \nonumber \\ & = & P(X=2 | X > 1)P(X > 1) \nonumber \\ & = & \frac{1}{1000} \times \frac{1000}{1000} \nonumber \end{eqnarray}\]

Similarly, \[\begin{eqnarray} P(X=3 \cap X > 2) & = & P(X=3 \cap X > 2| X > 2)P(X > 2) \phantom{00}\text{Definition of conditional probability} \nonumber \\ & = & P(X=3 | X > 2)P(X > 2) \nonumber \\ & = & \frac{2}{1000} \times (1- (P(X=2) + P(X=1))) \nonumber \\ & = & \frac{2}{1000} \times \left(1- \frac{1}{1000}\right) \nonumber \end{eqnarray}\]

This can be repeated for \(k = 1, 2, \ldots, 1001\)

\[\begin{eqnarray} P(X=k) & = & P(X=k | X > k-1)P(X > k-1) \nonumber \\ & = & \frac{k-1}{1000}\left(1 - \sum_{i=1}^{k-1}P(X=i)\right) \nonumber \end{eqnarray}\]

(b) What is the expected value for \(X\)?

\(E[X] = \sum_{k=1}^{n+1} k P(X=k) = 40.30\) See R-output below for calculation.

(c) What is the variance for \(X\)?

\(\text{Var}(X) = \sum_{k=1}^{n+1} k^2 P(X=k) - E[X]^2 = 415.95\) See R-output below for calculation.

nsongs <- 1000

## Vector of possible values of x for x=1,...,1001
xk <- 1:(nsongs+1)

## (Placeholder) vector of probabilities of P(X=x) for x=1,...,1001
pk <- rep(0, nsongs+1)

## Compute vector of probabilities of P(X=x) for x=1,...,1001 in a loop
for(k in 1:length(pk)){
    pk[k] <- (k-1)/nsongs * (1-sum(pk[1:(k-1)]))
}

EX <- sum(pk * xk)
VX <- sum(pk * xk^2) - EX^2

EX; VX
## [1] 40.30321
## [1] 415.9542

2009 midterm Problem 2

Q7

\[\begin{align*} E[\bar{X}^2] &= var(\bar{X}) + E[\bar{X}]^2 \\ &= \frac{1}{n^2}var\Big(\sum_{i=1}^n X_i\Big) + \Big(\frac{1}{n}E\Big[\sum_{i=1}^n X_i\Big]\Big)^2 \\ &= \frac{1}{n^2}\Big(\sum_{i=1}^n var(X_i)\Big) + \Big(\frac{1}{n}nE[X_1]\Big)^2 \;\;\;\; \text{(}X_1,X_2,...,X_n\text{ are iid)} \\ &= \frac{1}{n^2}n\sigma_1^2+\mu_1^2 \\ &= \frac{1}{n}\sigma_1^2+\mu_1^2 \\ E[Z] & = (\sigma_1^2+\sigma_2^2)/n+\mu_1^2+\mu_2^2. \end{align*}\]

2009 midterm Problem 6-8

Q6

\(c\) should be positive and the density should integrate to 1. \[ \int_0^{\infty} ce^{-\frac{x}{10}}dx = c(-10e^{-\frac{x}{10}})\Big|_0^{\infty}=10c. \]

Set \(10c=1\) and we have \(c=1/10\).

Q7

The survival function is \[\begin{align*} S(t) = P(X>t) = \int_t^{\infty}\frac{1}{10}e^{-1/10}dx = (-e^{-\frac{x}{10}})\Big|_t^{\infty}=e^{-t/10}. \end{align*}\]

The probability that a subject from this population survives more than 15 years is \[S(15) = e^{-15/10} = 0.22\]

Q8

To calculate the median survival time, solve the equation \(S(t)=0.5\). Therefore \[t_{median} = -10\log(0.5)\approx 6.93\].
